00:00:01.540 --> 00:00:05.358
Professor Ben Polak: So
this is what we did last time:

00:00:05.358 --> 00:00:09.240
we looked at a game involving
an entrant and an incumbent in a

00:00:09.240 --> 00:00:11.978
market;
and the entrant had to decide

00:00:11.978 --> 00:00:14.580
whether to enter that market or
not;

00:00:14.580 --> 00:00:17.730
and if they stayed out the
incumbent remained a monopolist;

00:00:17.730 --> 00:00:20.850
and the monopolist made 3
million in profit.

00:00:20.850 --> 00:00:23.952
If the entrant goes in,
then the incumbent can decide

00:00:23.952 --> 00:00:27.114
whether to accommodate the
entrant and just settle for

00:00:27.114 --> 00:00:29.680
duopoly profits,
making a million each;

00:00:29.680 --> 00:00:33.354
or the incumbent can fight,
in which case the incumbent

00:00:33.354 --> 00:00:37.710
makes no money at all and the
entrant loses a million dollars.

00:00:37.710 --> 00:00:40.060
We pointed out a number of
things about this game.

00:00:40.060 --> 00:00:44.483
One was that when we analyzed
it in a matrix form we quickly

00:00:44.483 --> 00:00:48.306
found that there were two Nash
Equilibria, that Nash

00:00:48.306 --> 00:00:51.230
Equilibrium were:
in and not fight;

00:00:51.230 --> 00:00:55.468
and out and fight.
But we argued that backward

00:00:55.468 --> 00:00:59.053
induction tells us that the
sensible answer is in and not

00:00:59.053 --> 00:01:01.409
fight.
Once the incumbent knows the

00:01:01.409 --> 00:01:05.160
entrant is in they're not going
to fight because 1 is bigger

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:08.719
than 0, and the entrant
anticipating this will enter.

00:01:08.719 --> 00:01:11.482
When we talked a little bit
more we said this other

00:01:11.482 --> 00:01:14.135
equilibrium, this out fight
equilibrium--it is an

00:01:14.135 --> 00:01:17.339
equilibrium because if the
entrant believes the incumbent's

00:01:17.339 --> 00:01:20.599
going to fight then the entrant
is going to stay out,

00:01:20.599 --> 00:01:24.395
and it's costless for the
incumbent to "fight" if in fact

00:01:24.395 --> 00:01:28.055
the entrant does stay out
because they never get called

00:01:28.055 --> 00:01:31.593
upon to fight anyway.
So the idea of this was that

00:01:31.593 --> 00:01:35.805
for the incumbent to say they're
going to fight is an "incredible

00:01:35.805 --> 00:01:38.030
threat."
That's terrible English.

00:01:38.030 --> 00:01:39.580
It's the way it is always
taught in the textbooks.

00:01:39.580 --> 00:01:43.010
It needs to be called a "not
credible" threat.

00:01:43.010 --> 00:01:45.072
And that "not credible" threat
is: he's not really going to

00:01:45.072 --> 00:01:47.240
fight if the entrant comes in,
and therefore,

00:01:47.240 --> 00:01:51.364
the entrant should come in and
in fact the incumbent will

00:01:51.364 --> 00:01:54.060
accommodate it.
So what we've shown here is

00:01:54.060 --> 00:01:56.851
that, if we believe this
argument, then the entrant will

00:01:56.851 --> 00:01:59.489
come in and the incumbent is
going to let him in.

