00:10:20.340 --> 00:10:23.264
But now we go to the eighth guy.
We've just argued that the

00:10:23.264 --> 00:10:26.080
tenth guy's coming in anyway and
Ale's going to give in to him.

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:27.844
We've argued the ninth guy's
coming in, so Ale's going to

00:10:27.844 --> 00:10:29.608
give in to this guy as well
because you can't put off the

00:10:29.608 --> 00:10:31.579
tenth guy.
And therefore we know that once

00:10:31.579 --> 00:10:34.294
we get to the eighth guy,
once again, he can safely come

00:10:34.294 --> 00:10:37.205
in because Ale knows by backward
induction he can't keep the

00:10:37.205 --> 00:10:39.179
ninth and the tenth guy out
anyway,

00:10:39.179 --> 00:10:41.513
and so this guy should come in
as well, and if we do this

00:10:41.513 --> 00:10:47.850
argument all the way back,
what do we get?

00:10:47.850 --> 00:10:50.750
He lets everybody in.
Everybody should come in and he

00:10:50.750 --> 00:10:54.230
should let everybody in.
So we have a problem here.

00:10:54.230 --> 00:10:56.965
We have a problem.
Backward induction says,

00:10:56.965 --> 00:11:00.559
even with these ten markets,
Ale in fact should let

00:11:00.559 --> 00:11:03.488
everybody in.
Everyone should know that,

00:11:03.488 --> 00:11:06.769
so they should come in.
So there's a disconnect here.

00:11:06.769 --> 00:11:09.579
There's a disconnect between
what the theory is telling

00:11:09.579 --> 00:11:12.545
us--backward induction is
telling us Ale can't keep people

00:11:12.545 --> 00:11:15.531
out by threatening to fight,
by establishing a reputation

00:11:15.531 --> 00:11:17.889
--, and what we actually just
saw, what happened,

00:11:17.889 --> 00:11:20.951
which was Ale did fight and did
keep people out,

00:11:20.951 --> 00:11:24.470
and we know that other
monopolist's do that as well.

00:11:24.470 --> 00:11:29.919
So how can we make rigorous
this idea of reputation?

00:11:29.919 --> 00:11:32.480
It's not captured by what we've
done so far in the class.

00:11:32.480 --> 00:11:35.788
So how can we bring back what
must be true in some sense--it's

00:11:35.788 --> 00:11:37.502
intuition that,
by fighting,

00:11:37.502 --> 00:11:41.600
Ale could keep people out and
therefore will keep people out.

00:11:41.600 --> 00:11:47.009
So to make that idea work I
want to introduce a new idea.

00:11:47.009 --> 00:11:51.124
And the new idea is that,
with very small probability,

00:11:51.124 --> 00:11:53.919
let's say 1% chance,
Ale is crazy.

00:11:53.919 --> 00:11:57.139
So stand up a second,
so he looks like a normal kind

00:11:57.139 --> 00:12:00.990
of guy but there's just 1%
chance that he's really bonkers.

00:12:00.990 --> 00:12:04.970
There's a 1% chance that he's
actually Rahul.

00:12:04.970 --> 00:12:10.455
So now let's redo the
analysis--And what do I mean by

00:12:10.455 --> 00:12:12.813
bonkers?
By bonkers, I mean,

00:12:12.813 --> 00:12:16.379
with 1%, Ale is the kind of guy
who likes to fight.

00:12:16.379 --> 00:12:19.348
So with 1% chance,
he's actually not got these

00:12:19.348 --> 00:12:21.872
payoffs at all;
he's actually got some

00:12:21.872 --> 00:12:24.868
different payoffs,
which are payoffs of somebody

00:12:24.868 --> 00:12:28.628
who--okay he'll lose money--but
he so much enjoys a fight he

00:12:28.628 --> 00:12:31.590
gets +10 here.
That's the bonkers guy's payoff.

00:12:31.590 --> 00:12:35.080
But there's only 1% chance he's
this bonkers guy.

00:12:35.080 --> 00:12:38.200
So now what happens?
Let's just walk it through.

00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:42.073
With 1% chance,
if there was only one market,

00:12:42.073 --> 00:12:45.533
not the ten markets.
So there's only one market and

00:12:45.533 --> 00:12:47.919
this one market was--I've
forgotten your name?

00:12:47.919 --> 00:12:48.599
Student: Isabella.
Professor Ben Polak:

00:12:48.599 --> 00:12:49.240
Isabella, who was in which
market, I've forgotten.

00:12:49.240 --> 00:12:51.276
Student: Miami.
Professor Ben Polak: In

00:12:51.276 --> 00:12:54.613
Miami, then she doesn't really
much care about the 1% chance

00:12:54.613 --> 00:12:57.509
that Ale is actually Rahul.
That doesn't really bother her

00:12:57.509 --> 00:13:00.057
very much, why?
Because with 99% chance Ale's

00:13:00.057 --> 00:13:03.149
going to give way and that's
good enough odds.

00:13:03.149 --> 00:13:06.120
With 99% chance she's happy to
come in.

00:13:06.120 --> 00:13:09.000
So if there was only one market
here, we'd be done.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.020
But with ten markets things are
a little different.

00:13:12.020 --> 00:13:15.003
Why? Let's see why.
So suppose in fact that

00:13:15.003 --> 00:13:19.551
Isabella in Miami thinks that
Ale--and everybody else thinks

00:13:19.551 --> 00:13:23.620
Ale is a pretty sane guy.
With 99% probability he's a

00:13:23.620 --> 00:13:27.440
sane guy, and Isabella enters
and everyone sees this.

00:13:27.440 --> 00:13:31.383
And to everyone's surprise,
rather than doing the sane

00:13:31.383 --> 00:13:36.145
thing, which is letting Isabella
in and switching to a duopoly in

00:13:36.145 --> 00:13:38.481
Miami,
what happens,

00:13:38.481 --> 00:13:44.970
in fact, after Isabella comes
in is that Ale fights.

00:13:44.970 --> 00:13:48.145
Okay, so now it's too late for
Isabella, she's lost her money,

00:13:48.145 --> 00:13:50.800
but our second market is,
what's your name again?

00:13:50.800 --> 00:13:51.993
Student: Scott.
 Professor Ben Polak:

00:13:51.993 --> 00:13:53.460
Scott, which market were you?
Student: Madison.

00:13:53.460 --> 00:13:56.133
Professor Ben Polak: So
Scott in Madison has observed

00:13:56.133 --> 00:13:58.626
what happened in Miami and
initially he thought that Ale

00:13:58.626 --> 00:14:01.329
was Ale.
99% probability Ale was this

00:14:01.329 --> 00:14:03.720
sane, nice, calm,
Italian guy.

00:14:03.720 --> 00:14:07.148
But on the other hand,
he just saw this sane,

00:14:07.148 --> 00:14:11.121
calm, Italian guy fight,
as he shouldn't have fought

00:14:11.121 --> 00:14:15.095
because of backward
induction--fought the entrant in

00:14:15.095 --> 00:14:18.376
Miami.
So now Scott thinks to himself:

00:14:18.376 --> 00:14:22.009
hmm, I'm not so sure that Ale
is this sane guy.

00:14:22.009 --> 00:14:24.765
Maybe I should update my
beliefs in the direction of

00:14:24.765 --> 00:14:27.629
thinking that Ale might actually
be the insane guy.

00:14:27.629 --> 00:14:31.864
So maybe--we're up to maybe a
probability 1/3 that Ale's

00:14:31.864 --> 00:14:33.983
actually insane.
So he thinks:

00:14:33.983 --> 00:14:36.690
okay, probability 1/3 that's
still not very much,

00:14:36.690 --> 00:14:38.438
I'll still risk it,
he comes in,

00:14:38.438 --> 00:14:42.420
and Ale fights him again.
It's a probability 1/3 he's

00:14:42.420 --> 00:14:43.909
sane.
He's going to give in to me.

00:14:43.909 --> 00:14:45.980
He comes in--Ale fights him
again.

00:14:45.980 --> 00:14:48.970
So now we're in the third
market, which was which market?

00:14:48.970 --> 00:14:49.630
Student: Bridgeport.
Professor Ben Polak:

00:14:49.630 --> 00:14:51.659
Bridgeport.
And Bridgeport's seen this

00:14:51.659 --> 00:14:56.263
horrible fight going on in Miami
and this horrible fight going on

00:14:56.263 --> 00:14:58.777
in Madison,
and now he's getting pretty

00:14:58.777 --> 00:15:01.680
sure that this nice,
calm, looking Ale is not nice,

00:15:01.680 --> 00:15:04.159
calm, looking Ale.
He's crazy Rahul.

00:15:04.159 --> 00:15:06.730
There's lot of evidence that
he's crazy Rahul.

00:15:06.730 --> 00:15:08.820
He's fought the last two
markets making huge losses.

00:15:08.820 --> 00:15:10.100
It must be that Ale likes to
fight.

00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:13.355
So what does he do?
He says, I'm going to stay out

00:15:13.355 --> 00:15:16.059
of here.
I'm convinced that this guy may

00:15:16.059 --> 00:15:19.556
be crazy, so I'll stay out.
And all the subsequent markets,

00:15:19.556 --> 00:15:22.750
they think: oh well you know he
fought these first two markets,

00:15:22.750 --> 00:15:25.066
that means he must be a crazy
guy or at least there's a high

00:15:25.066 --> 00:15:26.480
probability that he's a crazy
guy,

00:15:26.480 --> 00:15:29.114
so they all stay out which is
exactly what happened until we

00:15:29.114 --> 00:15:31.734
got to here.
And even here when they came in

00:15:31.734 --> 00:15:35.668
Ale acted liked crazy Rahul.
So what made that argument

00:15:35.668 --> 00:15:38.971
possible was what?
What made that argument

00:15:38.971 --> 00:15:43.098
possible was the small
possibility, the 1% possibility

00:15:43.098 --> 00:15:45.413
that Ale is bonkers.
But you know,

00:15:45.413 --> 00:15:47.740
how well do you know Ale?
There's a 1% chance he's

00:15:47.740 --> 00:15:50.017
bonkers.
How many of you think you're

00:15:50.017 --> 00:15:52.200
really sure that he's a sane
guy?

00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:54.850
He supports Italian football
teams, he's got to be pretty

00:15:54.850 --> 00:15:58.549
crazy, right?
So what happened here?

00:15:58.549 --> 00:16:04.455
This small possibility that Ale
is crazy allowed him to build up

00:16:04.455 --> 00:16:08.580
a reputation that kept all these
guys out,

00:16:08.580 --> 00:16:11.159
but actually the argument is
stronger than that.

00:16:11.159 --> 00:16:13.049
Let's try and push this
argument harder.

00:16:13.049 --> 00:16:17.259
Suppose, in fact,
that Ale is not crazy.

00:16:17.259 --> 00:16:20.015
Suppose that Ale is the sane
Ale, the nice,

00:16:20.015 --> 00:16:24.509
calm, Ale we all know and love.
But we've just argued that if

00:16:24.509 --> 00:16:29.007
Ale acts as if he's the crazy
guy then you're going to be

00:16:29.007 --> 00:16:32.059
convinced that he is the crazy
guy,

00:16:32.059 --> 00:16:36.469
so by acting crazy he might be
able to convince you that he is

00:16:36.469 --> 00:16:39.000
crazy and therefore keep you
out.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:42.402
So we argued before that,
if there's some chance that

00:16:42.402 --> 00:16:45.019
Ale's crazy, by acting crazy
early on,

00:16:45.019 --> 00:16:47.532
he's going to deter these late
entrants from entering the

00:16:47.532 --> 00:16:50.044
market because they think
they're fighting Rahul and they

00:16:50.044 --> 00:16:53.540
don't want to fight Rahul.
But we said these early guys,

00:16:53.540 --> 00:16:56.730
they had probability .99 that
he was sane;

00:16:56.730 --> 00:16:59.479
and .6 that he was sane;
and maybe even .5 he was sane

00:16:59.479 --> 00:17:01.440
here--so they thought of coming
in.

00:17:01.440 --> 00:17:05.089
But now we're arguing that even
if Ale is sane,

00:17:05.089 --> 00:17:08.660
even if he's that sane guy,
a rational guy,

00:17:08.660 --> 00:17:14.353
he should behave as if he's
crazy in order to keep these

00:17:14.353 --> 00:17:17.727
late guys out.
And these early players knowing

00:17:17.727 --> 00:17:20.830
that even the sane version of
Ale is going to fight them,

00:17:20.830 --> 00:17:23.165
should also stay out.
Now notice something's happened

00:17:23.165 --> 00:17:24.829
here.
They're not staying out because

00:17:24.829 --> 00:17:27.200
they think Ale's crazy,
they're staying out because

00:17:27.200 --> 00:17:30.045
they know that even the sane
version of Ale is going to fight

00:17:30.045 --> 00:17:32.730
them in order to seem crazy,
is that right?

00:17:32.730 --> 00:17:34.029
Everyone see that's a stronger
argument?

00:17:34.029 --> 00:17:37.071
So now even these early guys
are going to stay out of the

00:17:37.071 --> 00:17:40.279
market.
Now we're almost there.

00:17:40.279 --> 00:17:43.655
What we've argued--let's just
make sure we get the two pieces

00:17:43.655 --> 00:17:48.661
of this on the board.
We've argued that if there's an

00:17:48.661 --> 00:17:52.852
epsilon chance,
a very small chance,

00:17:52.852 --> 00:17:58.599
let's call it a 1% chance where
Ale is crazy,

00:17:58.599 --> 00:18:11.597
then he can deter entry by
fighting, i.e.,

00:18:11.597 --> 00:18:18.329
seeming crazy.
We argued that what really

00:18:18.329 --> 00:18:22.031
makes this argument strong is
once we realize that the sane

00:18:22.031 --> 00:18:24.852
person's going to act crazy,
we really know that everyone's

00:18:24.852 --> 00:18:26.339
going to act crazy and therefore
we should stay out.

00:18:26.339 --> 00:18:28.789
Now that argument won't quite
be right.

00:18:28.789 --> 00:18:31.127
So that's enough of the
argument I want you to have for

00:18:31.127 --> 00:18:33.465
the purpose of the exam,
but let me just point out that

00:18:33.465 --> 00:18:35.109
that argument isn't quite
correct.

00:18:35.109 --> 00:18:36.890
That can't quite be an
equilibrium.

00:18:36.890 --> 00:18:39.150
Now why can't that be an
equilibrium?

00:18:39.150 --> 00:18:42.309
We've just argued that even the
sane version of Ale--so this is

00:18:42.309 --> 00:18:45.469
a sort of slightly more subtle
argument so just pay attention a

00:18:45.469 --> 00:18:47.797
second.
We've argued that even the sane

00:18:47.797 --> 00:18:50.589
version of Ale is going to act
like a crazy guy.

00:18:50.589 --> 00:18:57.589
So if anyone came in,
he's going to act crazy anyway.

00:18:57.589 --> 00:18:59.789
So you're not going to update
your belief as to whether he's

00:18:59.789 --> 00:19:01.988
crazy or sane because we know
that the crazy guy is going to

00:19:01.988 --> 00:19:04.187
fight because he likes fighting
and the sane guy is going to

00:19:04.187 --> 00:19:06.200
fight because he wants to seem
like a crazy guy.

00:19:06.200 --> 00:19:08.145
So you're really learning
nothing whether your observe him

00:19:08.145 --> 00:19:10.720
fighting or now.
But now let's go back to our

00:19:10.720 --> 00:19:13.799
tenth market,
way back in our tenth market.

00:19:13.799 --> 00:19:18.302
Our tenth market participant,
whose name was Andy,

00:19:18.302 --> 00:19:21.609
hasn't learned anything about
Ale.

00:19:21.609 --> 00:19:25.258
He hasn't learned anything
because whether Ale was sane or

00:19:25.258 --> 00:19:28.405
crazy he's going to fight.
So observing what his actions

00:19:28.405 --> 00:19:31.069
early on, if that was really an
equilibrium, our tenth guy

00:19:31.069 --> 00:19:33.079
wouldn't have updated his belief
at all,

00:19:33.079 --> 00:19:35.178
and therefore,
would still believe with

00:19:35.178 --> 00:19:38.325
probability .99 that Ale was
sane, in which case our tenth

00:19:38.325 --> 00:19:41.347
guy would enter.
Once again, that argument would

00:19:41.347 --> 00:19:44.704
unravel from the back.
So what I described before

00:19:44.704 --> 00:19:48.296
can't quite be an equilibrium.
It can't be just as simple as

00:19:48.296 --> 00:19:51.001
all sane guys are going to act
crazy because then you wouldn't

00:19:51.001 --> 00:19:52.713
learn anything.
So it turns out that the

00:19:52.713 --> 00:19:54.579
equilibrium in this model is
actually very subtle,

00:19:54.579 --> 00:19:55.950
and it involves mixed
strategies,

00:19:55.950 --> 00:19:57.588
and mixed strategies are
something we did in the first

00:19:57.588 --> 00:19:59.634
half of the semester,
so we don't want to go back to

00:19:59.634 --> 00:20:00.858
it now.
So trust me,

00:20:00.858 --> 00:20:04.983
you can solve this out with
mixed strategies and the basic

00:20:04.983 --> 00:20:08.679
idea I gave you is right.
The basic idea is sane guys are

00:20:08.679 --> 00:20:12.018
occasionally going to act like
crazy guys in order to establish

00:20:12.018 --> 00:20:15.886
a reputation,
and that reputation helps them

00:20:15.886 --> 00:20:19.369
down the tree.
So this idea that even when

00:20:19.369 --> 00:20:23.034
there's a chain store,
people will enter--even when

00:20:23.034 --> 00:20:26.773
Ale has ten monopolies,
people will enter--this is a

00:20:26.773 --> 00:20:29.859
famous idea.
It's called the Chain Store

00:20:29.859 --> 00:20:33.945
Paradox, and it's due to a guy
called Selten who actually won

00:20:33.945 --> 00:20:37.224
the Nobel Prize.
This is the Chain Store Paradox

00:20:37.224 --> 00:20:40.809
and this idea of establishing
reputation is a big idea.

00:20:40.809 --> 00:20:45.995
The idea is once again you
might want to behave as if

00:20:45.995 --> 00:20:51.680
you're someone else in order to
deter people's actions,

00:20:51.680 --> 00:20:54.849
in order to affect people's
actions down the tree.

00:20:54.849 --> 00:20:59.080
Okay, so what have we learned
here?

00:20:59.080 --> 00:21:05.335
Let's just work it out.
So the first thing we learned

00:21:05.335 --> 00:21:08.660
was kind of a nerdy point,
but let me make it anyway.

00:21:08.660 --> 00:21:12.461
Introducing just a very,
very small probability,

00:21:12.461 --> 00:21:17.071
just a tiny probability that
Ale might be someone else--he

00:21:17.071 --> 00:21:19.918
might be a Rahul,
he might be crazy,

00:21:19.918 --> 00:21:23.556
he must like fights--that very
small probability radically

00:21:23.556 --> 00:21:27.865
changes the outcome of the game.
If we were all 100% sure he was

00:21:27.865 --> 00:21:31.480
sane we'd be tied by backward
induction and entry would

00:21:31.480 --> 00:21:33.742
follow.
He wouldn't be able to keep

00:21:33.742 --> 00:21:36.171
anybody out.
But that small probability

00:21:36.171 --> 00:21:38.920
allows us to get a very
different outcome.

00:21:38.920 --> 00:21:41.009
That's the first point I want
to draw into this.

00:21:41.009 --> 00:21:45.795
The second point I want to get
out of this, is really this idea

00:21:45.795 --> 00:21:48.730
of reputation.
There are lots of settings in

00:21:48.730 --> 00:21:52.426
society where reputation matters
and one of them is a reputation

00:21:52.426 --> 00:21:55.597
to fight.
How many of you have friends

00:21:55.597 --> 00:21:59.768
who have somewhat short fuses?
You know people who have short

00:21:59.768 --> 00:22:01.810
fuses, right?
When you're going out,

00:22:01.810 --> 00:22:05.424
choosing some movie to go to
with these guys who have short

00:22:05.424 --> 00:22:09.163
fuses or trying to decide who's
going to order something at a

00:22:09.163 --> 00:22:11.396
restaurant,
or who's going to get to be

00:22:11.396 --> 00:22:14.099
which side when you're playing
some game, some video game.

00:22:14.099 --> 00:22:17.076
I claim, is this true,
that the people who have

00:22:17.076 --> 00:22:20.311
slightly short fuses,
slightly more often get their

00:22:20.311 --> 00:22:23.394
way, is that right?
If you have a sibling who has a

00:22:23.394 --> 00:22:26.480
short fuse, they slightly more
often get their way and that's

00:22:26.480 --> 00:22:28.519
exactly this idea.
They have short fuses,

00:22:28.519 --> 00:22:31.136
the fact that they tend to blow
up and get angry at you gives

00:22:31.136 --> 00:22:32.750
them a little bit of an
advantage.

00:22:32.750 --> 00:22:35.124
And notice that maybe they
don't have a short fuse at all,

00:22:35.124 --> 00:22:37.498
maybe they're just pretending
to have a short fuse because

00:22:37.498 --> 00:22:40.040
they know they're going to get
their way over you softies more

00:22:40.040 --> 00:22:42.063
often.
None of you have short fuses,

00:22:42.063 --> 00:22:44.379
you're all sane people right?
So this idea,

00:22:44.379 --> 00:22:47.851
it should be a familiar idea to
you, but it's not just an idea

00:22:47.851 --> 00:22:50.470
in the sort of trivial world of
bargaining.

00:22:50.470 --> 00:22:55.089
Notice this idea of reputation
occurs all over the place.

00:22:55.089 --> 00:22:58.425
So another place it occurs,
somewhat grim place it occurs,

00:22:58.425 --> 00:23:01.000
is in the subject of hostage
negotiations.

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:03.671
In the subject of hostage
negotiations,

00:23:03.671 --> 00:23:07.607
when some other country has
seized some hostages from the

00:23:07.607 --> 00:23:09.247
U.S.
or maybe some criminal

