00:44:04.365 --> 00:44:08.228
with lower chance before P1.
Professor Ben Polak: All

00:44:08.228 --> 00:44:10.163
right, okay so you have two
arguments here,

00:44:10.163 --> 00:44:12.881
the first argument is maybe the
better shot will shoot first

00:44:12.881 --> 00:44:14.930
because,
after all, he has a higher

00:44:14.930 --> 00:44:17.512
chance of hitting.
And the other argument says

00:44:17.512 --> 00:44:20.219
maybe the worse shot will shoot
first, to what?

00:44:20.219 --> 00:44:23.739
To pre-empt the better shot
from shooting him.

00:44:23.739 --> 00:44:26.415
But now we get more
complicated, because after all,

00:44:26.415 --> 00:44:29.465
if you're the better shot and
you know that the worse shot

00:44:29.465 --> 00:44:32.515
maybe going to try and shoot
first to try and pre-empt you

00:44:32.515 --> 00:44:35.245
from shooting him,
you might be tempted to shoot

00:44:35.245 --> 00:44:38.135
before the worse shot shoots to
preempt the worse shot from

00:44:38.135 --> 00:44:39.980
pre-empting you from shooting
him.

00:44:39.980 --> 00:44:42.588
And if you're the worse shot
maybe you're going to try and

00:44:42.588 --> 00:44:45.006
shoot first, even earlier,
to pre-empt the better shot

00:44:45.006 --> 00:44:47.491
from pre-empting the worse shot,
from pre-empting the better

00:44:47.491 --> 00:44:49.469
