01:04:42.460 --> 01:04:47.610
remembering the answer.
Good, backward induction is the

01:04:47.610 --> 01:04:51.371
answer to all questions,
especially when you're asleep

01:04:51.371 --> 01:04:53.729
right.
Okay, so now we're going to use

01:04:53.729 --> 01:04:56.058
backward induction,
but where does backward

01:04:56.058 --> 01:05:00.100
induction start here?
Backward induction starts at

01:05:00.100 --> 01:05:05.135
the back of the game,
and what's the back of the game

01:05:05.135 --> 01:05:07.559
here?
The back of the game is where?

01:05:07.559 --> 01:05:10.333
It's when these two guys,
neither of them have thrown

01:05:10.333 --> 01:05:12.519
their sponge,
and they've reached here.

01:05:12.519 --> 01:05:15.500
So come here a second,
step, step.

01:05:15.500 --> 01:05:19.427
Let's assume it's Patrick's
turn, and they're absurdly

01:05:19.427 --> 01:05:22.170
close: they're uncomfortably
close.

01:05:22.170 --> 01:05:23.970
If they had longer noses they'd
be touching.

01:05:23.970 --> 01:05:28.887
They're at distance 0.
And at distance 0,

01:05:28.887 --> 01:05:33.579
at d = 0, let's suppose it's
Patrick's turn.

01:05:33.579 --> 01:05:35.003
So at d = 0,
no one has shot,

01:05:35.003 --> 01:05:37.037
it's Patrick's turn,
he's got the sponge,

01:05:37.037 --> 01:05:39.559
what should Patrick do?
Shout it out Patrick.

01:05:39.559 --> 01:05:41.154
Student: I should shoot.
Professor Ben Polak: You

01:05:41.154 --> 01:05:42.840
should shoot.
Patrick should shoot, right?

01:05:42.840 --> 01:05:48.344
At d = 0, say it's 2's turn,
and the answer is he should

01:05:48.344 --> 01:05:54.849
shoot because the probability of
it hitting at distance 0 is 1.

01:05:54.849 --> 01:05:57.183
Let's just move you to the side
a bit so that people can see the

01:05:57.183 --> 01:05:59.100
board.
I know it's an awkward dance

01:05:59.100 --> 01:06:01.590
but here you are--stop there:
that's good.

01:06:01.590 --> 01:06:06.949
So at distance 0 they should
certainly shoot.

01:06:06.949 --> 01:06:10.090
So now let's go back a step in
the backward induction.

01:06:10.090 --> 01:06:12.150
So we're at distance 1,
just take a step back.

01:06:12.150 --> 01:06:19.888
So take a step back,
it's Chevy's turn at distance

01:06:19.888 --> 01:06:23.039
1.
And what does Chevy know at

01:06:23.039 --> 01:06:24.820
distance 1?
Chevy what do you know?

01:06:24.820 --> 01:06:26.898
Shout it out.
Student: That Patrick

01:06:26.898 --> 01:06:29.331
will shoot next turn.
Professor Ben Polak:

01:06:29.331 --> 01:06:31.874
Right, so now Chevy knows that
Patrick's going to shoot

01:06:31.874 --> 01:06:34.523
tomorrow.
So which fact should Chevy use

01:06:34.523 --> 01:06:37.510
in deciding whether he should
shoot today?

01:06:37.510 --> 01:06:41.633
B.
He should use Fact B,

01:06:41.633 --> 01:06:52.210
and that tells us--so 1 knows
that 2 will shoot tomorrow,

01:06:52.210 --> 01:07:00.877
so by B, 1 should shoot if his
probability of hitting at

01:07:00.877 --> 01:07:08.756
distance 1 plus Patrick's
probability of hitting at

01:07:08.756 --> 01:07:14.840
distance 0,
if that is bigger than 1.

01:07:14.840 --> 01:07:17.639
Well is it bigger than 1?
Well let's have a look.

01:07:17.639 --> 01:07:20.790
We had a shot in here already,
we put a shot in here,

01:07:20.790 --> 01:07:22.849
and we're looking at distance
1.

01:07:22.849 --> 01:07:26.888
And so we're looking at this
distance here plus this distance

01:07:26.888 --> 01:07:29.490
here.
Is it bigger than 1?

01:07:29.490 --> 01:07:32.320
Yeah, it's bigger than 1.
Here's a bit more math.

01:07:32.320 --> 01:07:35.143
I lied to you before.
1 plus something is bigger than

01:07:35.143 --> 01:07:38.930
1.
So this is bigger than 1.

01:07:38.930 --> 01:07:44.284
So shoot.
Let's put it on our chart as

01:07:44.284 --> 01:07:45.674
shoot.
Let's go back a

01:07:45.674 --> 01:07:47.734
step--sorry--I'll have to have
Chevy do all the going

01:07:47.734 --> 01:07:49.590
backwards.
Now we're at distance what?

01:07:49.590 --> 01:07:53.768
We're at distance 2,
we're at d = 2,

01:07:53.768 --> 01:08:00.335
and it's Patrick's turn,
2's turn, and what does Patrick

01:08:00.335 --> 01:08:02.429
know?
Shout it out Patrick.

01:08:02.429 --> 01:08:04.253
Student: I know that
Chevy's going to shoot next

01:08:04.253 --> 01:08:05.985
turn.
Professor Ben Polak:

01:08:05.985 --> 01:08:08.811
Patrick knows that Chevy's going
to shoot next turn,

01:08:08.811 --> 01:08:11.360
so Patrick therefore should use
which fact?

01:08:11.360 --> 01:08:14.330
Fact B.
And Fact B tells him that he

01:08:14.330 --> 01:08:17.289
should shoot--let's just put
this in.

01:08:17.289 --> 01:08:22.836
So 2 knows that 1 will shoot
tomorrow, so by B it's all the

01:08:22.836 --> 01:08:28.145
same thing.
We know that 2 should shoot if

01:08:28.145 --> 01:08:29.771
P2[2]
+ P1[1]

01:08:29.771 --> 01:08:35.734
is bigger than 1,
and if we look at it on the

01:08:35.734 --> 01:08:41.020
board--here we are--it's 2's
turn,

01:08:41.020 --> 01:08:43.536
he's looking at this distance
plus this distance,

01:08:43.536 --> 01:08:46.820
and is it bigger than 1?
It is bigger than 1.

01:08:46.820 --> 01:08:51.944
So he should shoot.
And we can go on doing this

01:08:51.944 --> 01:08:55.740
argument backwards.,
We'll find that Chevy should

01:08:55.740 --> 01:09:00.010
shoot here because this plus
this is bigger than 1.

01:09:00.010 --> 01:09:02.301
And we'll know that here
Patrick once again will know

01:09:02.301 --> 01:09:04.020
that Chevy's going to shoot
tomorrow,

01:09:04.020 --> 01:09:05.805
so he should use Fact B,
so he should shoot provided

01:09:05.805 --> 01:09:07.380
this plus this is bigger than 1,
but it is.

01:09:07.380 --> 01:09:10.795
Now, we're back at d* and the
question we had at d*-- the

01:09:10.795 --> 01:09:13.539
question we'd left hanging at
d*--was what?

01:09:13.539 --> 01:09:17.383
At d* we knew already that
Chevy would not shoot if he

01:09:17.383 --> 01:09:21.010
thought Patrick was not going to
shoot tomorrow,

01:09:21.010 --> 01:09:23.192
but he should shoot if thinks
Patrick is going to shoot

01:09:23.192 --> 01:09:24.930
tomorrow, but what does Chevy
know at d*?

01:09:24.930 --> 01:09:26.229
Student: I know Patrick
is going to shoot.

01:09:26.229 --> 01:09:28.208
Professor Ben Polak: He
knows Patrick's going to shoot,

01:09:28.208 --> 01:09:30.720
so he should shoot.
Is that right?

01:09:30.720 --> 01:09:33.820
He knows Patrick's going to
shoot by backward induction so

01:09:33.820 --> 01:09:35.710
he should shoot.
So we just solved this.

01:09:35.710 --> 01:09:39.605
What did we actually show?
We showed, have seats

01:09:39.605 --> 01:09:45.837
gentlemen--sorry to keep you up
here--we know that prior to d*

01:09:45.837 --> 01:09:52.069
no one will shoot--will not
shoot--and we know that at d*,

01:09:52.069 --> 01:09:56.479
and in fact at any point
further on, we should shoot.

01:09:56.479 --> 01:09:58.680
That's horrible writing but it
says shoot.

01:09:58.680 --> 01:10:04.010
So we've shown more than we
claimed.

01:10:04.010 --> 01:10:05.516
We claimed that the first shot
should occur at d*,

01:10:05.516 --> 01:10:07.390
and we've actually shown more
than that: we've shown that even

01:10:07.390 --> 01:10:10.029
if you went beyond d*,
and if somebody had forgotten

01:10:10.029 --> 01:10:13.010
to shoot at d*,
at least you should shoot now.

01:10:13.010 --> 01:10:14.665
Give me like two more minutes
or three more minutes to finish

01:10:14.665 --> 01:10:15.880
this up because we're at a high
point now.

01:10:15.880 --> 01:10:17.510
Everyone okay to wait a couple
of minutes?

01:10:17.510 --> 01:10:24.755
Okay, so what did we prove here?
We proved that the first shot

01:10:24.755 --> 01:10:30.489
occurs at d* whoever's turn it
is at d*.

01:10:30.489 --> 01:10:33.253
It wasn't that the best guy,
the better shot,

01:10:33.253 --> 01:10:36.331
should shoot first,
or the worse shot should shoot

01:10:36.331 --> 01:10:38.120
first.
It turned out that,

01:10:38.120 --> 01:10:41.237
given their abilities,
there was a critical distance

01:10:41.237 --> 01:10:44.278
at which they should shoot.
If you go back to the

01:10:44.278 --> 01:10:47.617
eighteenth century military
strategy, you should shoot when

01:10:47.617 --> 01:10:50.609
you see the whites of their
eyes, which is at d*.

01:10:50.609 --> 01:10:56.119
But we learned something else
on the way.

01:10:56.119 --> 01:10:59.167
I claimed we learned that if
you're patient and you go

01:10:59.167 --> 01:11:01.791
through things carefully,
that the arguments we've

01:11:01.791 --> 01:11:04.201
learned from the course so far,
dominance arguments and

01:11:04.201 --> 01:11:08.063
backward induction arguments,
can solve out a really quite

01:11:08.063 --> 01:11:11.220
hard problem.
This was hard.

01:11:11.220 --> 01:11:13.817
It would have been useful for
the guy in War and Peace,

01:11:13.817 --> 01:11:16.560
or in Onegin or the guys
cycling in the Tour de France,

01:11:16.560 --> 01:11:17.909
or you guys with your sponges
to know this.

01:11:17.909 --> 01:11:22.069
And we can solve this exactly
using backward induction,

01:11:22.069 --> 01:11:24.920
and everyone in the room can do
it.

01:11:24.920 --> 01:11:29.020
Let me just push the argument a
tiny bit further.

01:11:29.020 --> 01:11:32.058
One thing we've always asked in
this class, is okay that's fine

01:11:32.058 --> 01:11:34.264
if everyone knows what's going
on in the game:

01:11:34.264 --> 01:11:37.057
here we have our smart Yale
football players and they know

01:11:37.057 --> 01:11:39.925
how to play this game,
so they're going to shoot at

01:11:39.925 --> 01:11:41.779
the right time.
But what happens if,

01:11:41.779 --> 01:11:44.430
instead of playing another
smart Yale football player,

01:11:44.430 --> 01:11:47.529
they're playing some uneducated
probably simple-minded football

01:11:47.529 --> 01:11:51.750
player from,
say, Harvard.

01:11:51.750 --> 01:11:55.361
Now that changes things a bit
doesn't it because we know that

01:11:55.361 --> 01:11:58.010
the Yale football player is
sophisticated,

01:11:58.010 --> 01:11:59.790
has taken my class,
and knows that he should shoot

01:11:59.790 --> 01:12:01.970
at d*, but the Harvard guy
doesn't learn anything anymore,

01:12:01.970 --> 01:12:05.787
so they're stuck.
So if you're the Yale guy

01:12:05.787 --> 01:12:09.789
playing the Harvard guy how does
that change your decision?

01:12:09.789 --> 01:12:14.127
Should you shoot earlier than
d* when you're playing against

01:12:14.127 --> 01:12:17.363
the Harvard guy,
or later than d* when you're

01:12:17.363 --> 01:12:21.334
playing against the Harvard guy?
Let's try our Yale guys and see

01:12:21.334 --> 01:12:23.130
what they think,
what do you think Chevy?

01:12:23.130 --> 01:12:24.449
Student: Definitely not
earlier.

01:12:24.449 --> 01:12:25.968
Professor Ben Polak:
Definitely not earlier,

01:12:25.968 --> 01:12:27.189
that's the key thing right.
Now why?

01:12:27.189 --> 01:12:30.979
Why definitely not earlier?
Student: Because if you

01:12:30.979 --> 01:12:34.880
miss, the other person has a
probability of 1,

01:12:34.880 --> 01:12:38.260
you have a higher chance of
missing.

01:12:38.260 --> 01:12:42.340
Professor Ben Polak: All
right, so I claim Chevy's right.

01:12:42.340 --> 01:12:44.281
That's good because I've just
claimed that Yale football

01:12:44.281 --> 01:12:45.990
players are sophisticated.
Chevy's right,

01:12:45.990 --> 01:12:48.668
that even if you're playing
against a Harvard guy you

01:12:48.668 --> 01:12:51.398
shouldn't shoot before d*
because it was a dominant

01:12:51.398 --> 01:12:53.510
strategy not to shoot before
d*.

01:12:53.510 --> 01:12:56.378
It doesn't matter whether you
think the Harvard guy is going

01:12:56.378 --> 01:12:58.420
to be dumb enough to shoot early
or not.

01:12:58.420 --> 01:13:00.520
If he is dumb enough to shoot
early, so much the better.

01:13:00.520 --> 01:13:03.577
You should wait until D*.
Notice that argument doesn't

01:13:03.577 --> 01:13:05.989
depend on you playing against
somebody who is sophisticated,

01:13:05.989 --> 01:13:08.583
or someone who's less
sophisticated,

01:13:08.583 --> 01:13:13.029
like a Harvard football player,
or somebody who's basically a

01:13:13.029 --> 01:13:16.420
chair,
like a Harvard football player.

01:13:16.420 --> 01:13:19.455
You shouldn't shoot before d*
because it's a dominant strategy

01:13:19.455 --> 01:13:21.765
not to shoot before d*.
Now, you might want to wait a

01:13:21.765 --> 01:13:23.640
little to see if they're not
going to shoot early,

01:13:23.640 --> 01:13:25.904
to see if he's not going to
shoot, but you certainly

01:13:25.904 --> 01:13:28.434
shouldn't shoot early.
Let me finish with one other

01:13:28.434 --> 01:13:31.029
thing.
Every time when we've played

01:13:31.029 --> 01:13:35.010
this game in class,
whether it's here or up in SOM,

01:13:35.010 --> 01:13:40.010
people shoot too early.
They miss.

01:13:40.010 --> 01:13:42.392
You can do the econometrics on
this, you could figure out that,

01:13:42.392 --> 01:13:44.352
on average--average
abilities--I'm sometimes getting

01:13:44.352 --> 01:13:46.991
the better shots,
sometimes I'm getting the worse

01:13:46.991 --> 01:13:50.655
shots--on average I should see
people hitting about half of the

01:13:50.655 --> 01:13:53.891
time over a large sample.
But here I tend to see people

01:13:53.891 --> 01:13:56.290
miss, as we did today,
almost all the time.

01:13:56.290 --> 01:14:04.810
Why do we see so many misses?
So one problem may be that

01:14:04.810 --> 01:14:08.252
people are just overconfident.
They're overconfident on their

01:14:08.252 --> 01:14:10.842
ability to throw.
And there's a large literature

01:14:10.842 --> 01:14:13.760
in Economics about how people
tend to be overconfident.

01:14:13.760 --> 01:14:16.201
But there's another possible
explanation, and let me just

01:14:16.201 --> 01:14:18.250
push it past you as the last
thing for today.

01:14:18.250 --> 01:14:21.661
I think Americans--I think this
doesn't go for the

01:14:21.661 --> 01:14:25.560
Brits--Americans have what I
call a "pro-active bias."

01:14:25.560 --> 01:14:28.655
You guys are brought up since
you're in kindergarten--maybe

01:14:28.655 --> 01:14:31.430
before--and you're told you have
to be pro-active.

01:14:31.430 --> 01:14:33.840
You have "to make the world
come to you."

01:14:33.840 --> 01:14:37.970
And my evidence for this is
based on sophisticated empirical

01:14:37.970 --> 01:14:42.270
work watching Sports Center.
So on Sports Center when they

01:14:42.270 --> 01:14:45.760
interview these sweaty athletes
after the game,

01:14:45.760 --> 01:14:49.933
the sweaty athletes say,
it's great I now control my own

01:14:49.933 --> 01:14:52.560
destiny.
Well, I'm a Brit.

01:14:52.560 --> 01:14:55.088
I think controlling my own
destiny sounds kind of scary to

01:14:55.088 --> 01:14:56.310
me;
it doesn't sound like a good

01:14:56.310 --> 01:15:00.350
thing at all.
In fact, if I wanted to control

01:15:00.350 --> 01:15:05.489
my own destiny,
I wouldn't have got married.

01:15:05.489 --> 01:15:10.041
That's going to be edited off
the film, but the point I want

01:15:10.041 --> 01:15:12.829
to make is this.
Every time I play this game,

01:15:12.829 --> 01:15:15.479
when I ask people why they
shoot early I hear the same

01:15:15.479 --> 01:15:18.029
thing, and it's evidence to this
proactive bias.

01:15:18.029 --> 01:15:23.204
People say, well at least I
went down swinging and the

01:15:23.204 --> 01:15:28.476
problem is: the aim in life is
not to go down swinging,

01:15:28.476 --> 01:15:33.805
it's not to go down.
So one lesson to get from this

01:15:33.805 --> 01:15:38.779
lecture is, sometimes waiting is
a good strategy.

01:15:38.779 --> 01:15:41.000
Alright, and we'll come back to
it on Monday.

